<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE suite SYSTEM "https://testng.org/testng-1.0.dtd">

<!--
    WHAT IS THIS FILE?
    ==================
    This is the TestNG Suite XML file. It is the MASTER CONTROL FILE
    for your entire test automation project.

    Think of it like a TV remote control:
    You press one button (mvn test) and THIS file decides:
       - Which tests to run
       - In what order
       - How many at the same time (parallel)
       - Which browsers to use
       - What to do when a test fails

    You never run individual test classes manually in a real project.
    Everything is controlled from this one file.

    The DOCTYPE line below tells TestNG the rules and grammar for this XML.
    It is like saying "this file follows TestNG's official format".
-->

<!--
    SUITE — THE ENTIRE TEST RUN
    ============================
    This is the outermost tag that wraps everything.
    One suite = one full test execution (e.g. your nightly CI/CD run).

    ATTRIBUTES EXPLAINED:

    name="Automation Suite"
    → Just a label. This name appears in your test reports so you know
      which suite produced which results. Choose something meaningful.

    verbose="2"
    → Controls how much detail is printed in the console while tests run.
      0 = silent (nothing printed)
      1 = minimal (just pass/fail)
      2 = normal (test names, results) which is a good default
      5 = maximum (every internal TestNG step, useful for debugging)

    parallel="tests"
    → Tells TestNG to run multiple test blocks AT THE SAME TIME.
      Options:
        "none"    → Run everything one by one (slowest, safest)
        "tests"   → Run each test block in parallel (we use this)
        "classes" → Run each class in parallel
        "methods" → Run each @Test method in parallel (fastest, riskiest)
      For beginners: start with "none". Switch to "tests" when your
      tests are stable and independent of each other.

    thread-count="3"
    → How many tests to run simultaneously when parallel is enabled.
      Here we run 3 test blocks at the same time.
      Rule of thumb: match this to the number of CPU cores on your machine.
      Too high = your machine slows down. Start with 2 or 3.

    preserve-order="true"
    → Run the test blocks in the EXACT ORDER they appear in this file.
      If false, TestNG may reorder them. Always set to true in production
      so your report results are predictable and consistent.
-->
<suite name="Automation Suite"
       verbose="2"
       parallel="tests"
       thread-count="3"
       preserve-order="true">


    <!--
        SECTION 1: GLOBAL LISTENERS
        ============================
        What is a Listener?
        A listener is a Java class that "listens" to test events and
        reacts to them automatically.

        Events a listener can react to:
        → onTestStart    : fired when a test begins
        → onTestSuccess  : fired when a test passes
        → onTestFailure  : fired when a test fails
        → onTestSkipped  : fired when a test is skipped
        → onFinish       : fired when the entire suite finishes

        Real-world uses:
        → Take a screenshot automatically when a test fails
        → Log results to an Extent Report or Allure Report
        → Send a Slack or email notification when tests finish
        → Retry a failed test automatically

        Listeners listed here apply to ALL tests in the entire suite.
        You can also attach a listener to just one test block if needed.

        NOTE FOR BEGINNERS:
        The two listener classes below (TestListener and RetryListener)
        are Java classes YOU will write as your project grows.
        They do not exist yet. Once you create them in the
        framework/listeners/ package, uncomment this section.
    -->
    <!--
    <listeners>
        <listener class-name="framework.listeners.TestListener"/>
        <listener class-name="framework.listeners.RetryListener"/>
    </listeners>
    -->


    <!--
        SECTION 2: GOOGLE TESTS (Currently Active)
        ============================================
        This is the only test block active right now because
        GoogleTest is the only class that exists in the project.

        As you create more test classes, add new test blocks below
        following the same pattern as the smoke and regression
        examples shown in sections 3 and 4.
    -->
    <test name="Google Tests">
        <classes>
            <!--
                tests.GoogleTest means:
                → Look in the "tests" package (src/test/java/tests/)
                → Find the file "GoogleTest.java"
                → Run all @Test methods inside it
            -->
            <class name="tests.GoogleTest"/>
            <class name="tests.AdvancedTestNGFeaturesTest"/>
        </classes>
    </test>


    <!--
        SECTION 3: SMOKE TESTS (Uncomment when ready)
        ===============================================
        What is a Smoke Test?
        A quick, high-level check to verify the most critical features
        of your application are working BEFORE running deeper tests.
        Like checking if the engine starts before testing the whole car.
        Smoke tests are fast, usually 5 to 15 minutes maximum.
        They run first. If smoke tests fail, no point running regression.

        Typical smoke tests in a web app:
        → Can the user log in?
        → Does the home page load?
        → Is the main navigation working?

        In CI/CD pipelines, smoke tests run on EVERY code commit.

        GROUPS EXPLAINED:
        Groups let you TAG your @Test methods in Java and then choose
        which tags to run here in the XML.

        In your Java test class you would write:
            @Test(groups = {"smoke"})
            public void verifyLogin() { ... }

        Then here in XML, include name="smoke" means:
        → Only run @Test methods that have groups = "smoke"
        → Skip all other @Test methods in the listed classes

        Common group names used in industry:
        → "smoke"      : critical path tests, run on every commit
        → "regression" : full test suite, run nightly
        → "sanity"     : quick checks after a bug fix
        → "e2e"        : end-to-end user journey tests
    -->
    <!--
    <test name="Smoke Tests">
        <groups>
            <run>
                <include name="smoke"/>
            </run>
        </groups>
        <classes>
            <class name="tests.smoke.LoginTest"/>
            <class name="tests.smoke.HomePageTest"/>
        </classes>
    </test>
    -->


    <!--
        SECTION 4: REGRESSION TESTS (Uncomment when ready)
        ====================================================
        What is Regression Testing?
        After developers fix a bug or add a new feature, regression
        testing checks that NOTHING ELSE broke as a side effect.
        It covers a much wider set of scenarios than smoke tests.
        Regression tests are slower, can run 30 minutes to several hours.
        They typically run NIGHTLY (scheduled, not on every commit).

        Example: Developer adds a discount feature to checkout.
        Regression tests check:
        → Does checkout still work normally?
        → Is the cart still calculating totals correctly?
        → Did the login page break?
        → Did the profile page break?
    -->
    <!--
    <test name="Regression Tests">
        <groups>
            <run>
                <include name="regression"/>
            </run>
        </groups>
        <classes>
            <class name="tests.regression.CheckoutTest"/>
            <class name="tests.regression.CartTest"/>
        </classes>
    </test>
    -->


    <!--
        SECTION 5: CROSS-BROWSER TESTS (Uncomment when ready)
        =======================================================
        What is Cross-Browser Testing?
        Your website must work correctly on ALL major browsers:
        Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari.
        Cross-browser tests run the SAME test scenarios on DIFFERENT
        browsers to catch browser-specific bugs.

        Example bug caught by cross-browser testing:
        A dropdown works on Chrome but does not open on Firefox.

        HOW PARAMETERS WORK:
        The parameter tag passes data from this XML into your Java test.

        name="browser"  → the variable name your Java code reads
        value="chrome"  → the actual value sent in at runtime

        In your Java class you read it like this:
            @Parameters({"browser"})
            public void setUp(String browser) {
                if (browser.equals("chrome"))  { driver = new ChromeDriver(); }
                if (browser.equals("firefox")) { driver = new FirefoxDriver(); }
            }

        To test Firefox, add another test block with value="firefox".
        Each block runs independently on its own browser.
    -->
    <!--
    <test name="Chrome Tests">
        <parameter name="browser" value="chrome"/>
        <classes>
            <class name="tests.crossbrowser.CrossBrowserTest"/>
        </classes>
    </test>

    <test name="Firefox Tests">
        <parameter name="browser" value="firefox"/>
        <classes>
            <class name="tests.crossbrowser.CrossBrowserTest"/>
        </classes>
    </test>
    -->


</suite>